We expect the total_rooms of houses to be strongly correlated with total_bedrooms. Use ggpairs() to investigate correlations between these two variables.

housing_prices %>% 
  select(total_rooms, total_bedrooms) %>% 
  ggpairs()
Warning in ggally_statistic(data = data, mapping = mapping, na.rm = na.rm,  :
  Removed 200 rows containing missing values
Warning: Removed 200 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
Warning: Removed 200 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Interpretation

The correlation coefficient comes out to 0.934, which corresponds to a very strong positive correlation. As you increase total rooms, total bedrooms also increases.

So, we do find significant correlations. Lets drop total_bedrooms from the dataset, and use only total_rooms going forward.

# remove total_bedrooms
housing_prices <- housing_prices %>% 
  select(-total_bedrooms)

Shortly we may try a regression model to fit the categorical predictor ocean_proximity. Investigate the level of ocean_proximity predictors. How many dummy variables do you expect to get from it?

housing_prices %>% 
  distinct(ocean_proximity)

Interpretation

Since there are 5 total levels of ocean_proximity, I would expect to have 4 dummy variables after one has been used as a reference.

Start with simple linear regression. Regress median_house_value on median_income and check the regression diagnostics.

model <- lm(median_house_value ~ median_income, data = housing_prices)

autoplot(model)


summary(model)

Call:
lm(formula = median_house_value ~ median_income, data = housing_prices)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-513966  -51564  -13979   36549  403935 

Coefficients:
              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)    45457.0     1359.0   33.45   <2e-16 ***
median_income  39987.0      339.9  117.64   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 74870 on 19673 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.4129,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.4129 
F-statistic: 1.384e+04 on 1 and 19673 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Interpretation

Residuals v Fitted The residuals form a steady horizontal line around 0, which suggests the variances of errors are roughly equal. However, the residuals dont quite bounce randomly around the zero line which suggests the linear relationship may not fit this data well.

Normal QQ Plot The points appears to wrap around the normal line loosely, Id have concerns here and suggest that the test of normality isnt passed. The data is potentially skewed.

Scale-Location There is a funnel effect that has formed, with the data going from wider to narrower for greater fitted values. This indicates that there isnt a constancy of variance in our residuals.

Adjusted R-Squared Our value comes to 0.4129. This tells us that 41.3% of the variance in our dependent variable (median_house_value) is explained by our independent variable (median_income). This gives a reasonable fit, however, with the earlier diagnostics shows that we can most likely do better.

Residual Standard Error this is a large value of 74870, again, this speaks to the variance of errors we witnessed in our diagnostic plots.

Interpretation

Residuals vs Fitted Again, the line is fairly horizontal around zero, however the residuals dont randomly bounce around the zero line which leads me to believe that it doesnt quite fit this linear relationship well.

Normal QQ Plot It is quite similar to before, it loosely falls on the normal line the middle part of our data, however, it is not close to that thereafter. There may be some concerns with the normality of our residuals.

Scale-Location There is a similar funnel effect for lower fitted values, but the line does keep fairly horizontal. There may still be some concern for the constancy of variance in our residuals.

Adjusted R Squared Our value has increased to 0.5528, a slightly better fit, however, we would expect an increase with the addition of any predictor. This now means that 55.3% of the variation in our response variable is explained by the predictor variables.

Residuals Standard Error This has decreased to 65340, an improvement on the previous model and a slightly better fit, however, it is still large.

Extension

Try adding an interaction between log(medium_income) and your chosen categorical predictor. Do you think this interaction term is statistically justified?

# add interaction between log(median_income) and ocean_proximity
model3 <- lm(median_house_value ~ median_income + log(median_income):ocean_proximity, 
             data = housing_prices)

# diagnostic plots for model3
autoplot(model3)


#summary of model3
summary(model3)

    data = housing_prices)

log(median_income):ocean_proximityISLAND       210999      29443   7.166 7.98e-13 ***

F-statistic:  3912 on 6 and 19668 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Interpretation

I dont believe this interaction term is statistically justified, based on the diagnostic plots and adjusted R Squared value.

In the Scale-Location plot the residuals appear to have a greater funnel effect. The residuals for lower fitted values appear much more spread than greater fitted values. The model appears to be a poor fit in terms of constancy of variation among residuals. It has not improved the model fit in terms of the other plots either.

The adjusted R-squared value has (slightly) increased to 54.4%. This is to be expected when adding further predictor variables, however, it does not add substantial fit in our model compared to what we had previously.
